Articles.Content: Just letting you guys know, RO does not seem to have RSS as a dependency in CKAN anymore.

Hello, I'd like to ask: does anyone manage to play RSS and RO and put up without hangar extender?

For some reason I'm having great difficulty with building tall rockets such as the FASA saturn V provided, it looks difficult if not impossible to place more than a few parts above the ceiling.

how do you people do it? is there a Hangar extender alternative that I'm unaware of? or are there any tricks about building taller?

Many thanks

If you go into part-offset mode ("2" on keyboard) and shift-left click the rocket, you'll offset the root part. Look up, and drag the whole thing into the floor to work on the upper stages. I think you might be able to launch it that way, but I pull it back up when I'm done to be safe.

Just letting you guys know, RO does not seem to have RSS as a dependency in CKAN anymore.

True. I don't know if it's intentional or not, but it's certainly a bit confusing.

If one forgets to install RSS and does so manually later, there are..glitches. The ground around space centres either uses a very dark brown texture or is black, there are issues with lighting (parts and buildings illuminated from another angle than the Sun is at), and spontaneously the "interior" of the planet is visible (similar to this)

To counter that: in CKAN, tick the RSS checkbox along with Realism Overhaul, choose a texture set and proceed as normally. Everything should work fine, or at least it did for me.

Not sure about periapsis, but you want both RealHeat and DeadlyReentry. DeadlyReentry is basically in stock now, so the mod is mostly about tweaking reentry to be more dangerous and realistic, while adding smaller features like G-Force damage. RealHeat is about improving the heat system and, in future, replacing parts of it. Starwaster mentioned he might need a another config in future to adapt DRE to RH, but atm everything should work fine together.

Edited July 12, 2015 by Astraph

And one more question - how should I treat parts described as "not supported by RO"? Are they still OK to use, or would they cause balance issues, be under- / overpowered, make the game buggy or something else?

If a part is "not supported by RO", then Realism Overhaul has no realism config for that part, meaning it is configured for stock. In the case of engines, non RO engines are under-powered, but things like stock solar panels are over-powered. The parts won't be buggy in flight because they shouldn't be buggy in the stock game. Personally, I don't touch non-RO parts, but I know some people who are fine with using them. So do whatever you want.

Jep, most extension mods like FAR or DRE work for both Stock and RO modified parts. If you have stock capsules in the wrong category or marked as non-RO, then your mod-install might be bugged. Otherwise not all mods are supported by RO, and some might be outdated and miss parts.

Btw, is it just for me that some nodes are borked? The stock storage compartment nodes are inside the part, same goes for a bunch of MK3 parts apart from the generic fuel tanks?

They are, the real command modules were quite a bit larger. Mercury and Apollo measured 1.9m and 3.9m diameter respectively, which was probably rounded up for practical reasons. If you need an aerodynamic configuration, use the produceral parts mod and create cone shaped structural parts/fuel tanks to stack them between parts of different sizes. Or ofc storage bays/proc interstage fairings.

If you want a smaller 3 man pod, try a soyuz mods. Should be, depending on variant, around 2.5m to 3m.
